09/03/2009
ANKARA, Turkey -- Police have detained five people suspected of planning to assassinate Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan, Turkish media reported on Monday (March 9th). 
The alleged plotters were reportedly planning to kill Erdogan in the southern province of Adana, where he attended a campaign rally Saturday. 
After the welcoming ceremony at the airport, local police received information of the plot. 
They first arrested a woman "with close ties to the military and security forces", media said. 
After interrogating her, police arrested the other four suspects. 
Adana Governor Ilhan Atis confirmed the arrests but released no further information. 
According to media reports, police are investigating a possible link to the shadowy secularist Ergenekon group.
In other news, Iranian border police fired on two Turkish boys at the Turkish-Iranian border, killing one and wounding the other, media reported on Sunday. 
Officials say the two brothers, aged 13 and 12, attempted to illegally cross the border with Iran in the eastern Turkish province of Van.
In other news Sunday, four children between the ages of one and six died when their home collapsed because of heavy rains in the southeastern province of Diyarbakir, local authorities said. 
Their parents and older brother survived. 
(Milliyet, Zaman, Anadolu news agency, Reuters - 09/03/09; Hurriyet, Dogan news agency, AFP - 08/03/09)
